SIMPLE: sump
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sump
<hw>Sump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>sumpf</ets>
a sump in a mine, a swamp, akin to LG. <ets>sump</ets>, D.
<ets>somp</ets> a swamp, Dan. & Sw. <ets>sump</ets>, and perhaps to E.
<ets>swamp</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>A round
pit of stone, lined with clay, for receiving the metal on its first
fusion.</def> <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The cistern or reservoir made at the lowest point of
a mine, from which is pumped the water which accumulates
there.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pond of water for salt works.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A puddle or dirty pool.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sump fuse</b></col>, <cd>a fuse used in blasting under
water.</cd> -- <col><b>Sump men</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>the
men who sink the sump in a mine.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sumph</ent>⟦br⟧
